sql:
SELECT AVG(element_size) AS average_element_size
FROM typed_arrays
WHERE constructor_name = 'Int8Array';

external_knowledge:
- "Heavyweight champion" refers to the project with the highest average execution time;
- "Across all its arrays" means the average execution time is calculated for all arrays associated with each project;
- The average execution time is computed by averaging the execution times of all operations within each array and then averaging these averages for each project.

- A "typed array" is a specialized data structure that holds a fixed number of elements of the same type;
- The "average element size" is the mean size in bytes of the elements in the typed arrays;
- "More than one typed array" implies the project has at least two typed arrays associated with it.

- 'Int8' refers to a specific type of data array element, typically an 8-bit integer;
- 'admin' is a role that indicates a user with administrative privileges;
- 'richer collection' implies a higher count of arrays compared to the average.

- `array_id` is a unique identifier for each array, similar to a city's unique name;
- `operation_name` represents different types of activities or tasks performed on the array;
- `execution_time` is the time taken to complete each operation, analogous to the duration of an activity;
- The query groups these activities by the city (array) they belong to and summarizes the total number of activities and the longest duration of a single activity.

- 'element_type' refers to the data type of the elements in the array;
- 'element_size' is the size of each element in bytes;
- 'typed_arrays' is a table that contains information about different types of elements and their sizes.

- "ancient scrolls" refers to the columns `constructor_name`, `element_type`, `element_size`, and `description` of the `typed_arrays` table;
- "evolved through more than one incarnation" means the array has more than one version, identified by the `version_id` in the `array_versions` table;
- "lightest to the heaviest" indicates the results should be ordered by `element_size` in ascending order.

- "Average execution time" refers to the mean value of the execution time metric;
- "Dependencies" in this context refer to arrays that are linked to other arrays through the `array_dependencies` table;
- "Level > 1" indicates that the array is not at the root level of the hierarchy but is a dependent array.

- "Most frequently visited flower" refers to the array that has been accessed the most times;
- "Stands tall with the best performance metrics" means the array has the best average performance metric value;
- "Latest version" refers to the most recent version number of the array;
- "Total time spent by gardeners (users) tending to it" refers to the sum of execution times for operations executed by users.

- "gardeners" refers to users who have created arrays;
- "planted more than one seed" means the user has created more than one array;
- "listed from the most prolific to the least" indicates the results are ordered by the total number of arrays in descending order.

- 'crafted arrays' refers to arrays created in the database;
- 'most recently crafted' is determined by the `created_at` timestamp;
- 'masterpieces in an artist's gallery' is a metaphor for the most recently created arrays;
- 'creators' refers to the users who created the arrays.

- "champions of performance" refers to the typed arrays with the highest average performance metrics;
- "average performance metrics" are calculated by averaging the `metric_value` for each `array_id` across all performance metrics;
- "rank in descending order" means the typed arrays are listed from the highest to the lowest average performance metric value.
